Dropping irrelevant columns:

In[60]:
# Normalize proportions to ensure they sum to 1
total_proportion = sum(occupation_proportions.values())
normalized_proportions = {k: v / total_proportion for k, v in occupation_proportions.items()}
In[61]:
# Extract categories and normalized proportions
categories = list(normalized_proportions.keys())
proportions = list(normalized_proportions.values())
In[62]:
# Assign null values proportionally
null_indices = df_appl['Occupation Type'].isnull()
df_appl.loc[null_indices, 'Occupation Type'] = np.random.choice(categories, size=null_indices.sum(), p=proportions)

Conclusion

      Through EDA, it became evident that detecting fraud involves addressing class imbalance and utilizing features with significant predictive power. Visualization techniques like box plots revealed distribution differences between fraud and non-fraud cases, while scaling of continuous variables like transaction time and amount ensured consistency
  •     For employment types, banks should consider focusing on individuals classified under 'Business Entity Type-3' and 'Self-Employed,' as these groups show promising repayment trends.
  •     Additionally, loans targeted at 'Working' individuals, particularly female employees, could be a strategic focus for better repayment reliability and customer engagement.
  •     These findings suggest that leveraging high-correlation features alongside balancing strategies can enhance the model's predictive accuracy for fraud detection
